SIMPLE: institution
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Institution
<hw>In`sti*tu"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>institutio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>institution</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or process of instituting; as: <sd>(a)</sd>
Establishment; foundation; enactment; <as>as, the <ex>institution</ex>
of a school</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>institution</qex> of God's law is described as being
established by solemn injunction.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>Instruction; education.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<au>Bentley.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Eccl. Law)</fld> <def>The act or
ceremony of investing a clergyman with the spiritual part of a benefice,
by which the care of souls is committed to his charge.</def>
<rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which instituted or established</def>; as:
<sd>(a)</sd> <def>Established order, method, or custom; enactment;
ordinance; permanent form of law or polity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The nature of our people,⟦br⟧
Our city's <qex>institutions</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>An established or organized society or corporation;
an establishment, especially of a public character, or affecting a
community; a foundation; <as>as, a literary <ex>institution</ex>; a
charitable <ex>institution</ex></as>; also, a building or the buildings
occupied or used by such organization; <as>as, the Smithsonian
<ex>Institution</ex></as>.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>Anything forming a
characteristic and persistent feature in social or national life or
habits.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We ordered a lunch (the most delightful of English
<qex>institutions</qex>, next to dinner) to be ready against our
return.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which institutes or instructs; a textbook; a
system of elements or rules; an institute.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is another manuscript, of above three hundred years old, . .
. being an <qex>institution</qex> of physic.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Institutional</ent>⟦br⟧
